why ALB having ipv4 or ipv6 does all ELB have ip?

Yes! Every ALB has an IP address — but it is not fixed, it changes!

Why ALB has IPs:

ALB DNS name:
myapp-alb-123.us-east-2.elb.amazonaws.com
        ↓
DNS resolves to IP addresses
        ↓
54.23.11.10   ← IP in us-east-2a
54.23.11.20   ← IP in us-east-2b

ALB runs across 2 AZs so it has at least 2 IPs — one per AZ.

AWS automatically scales the ALB and IPs change without warning. This is why you always use the DNS name, never the IP directly.

Do all ELB types have IPs?
Yes! All three AWS load balancer types have IPs:

ALB (Application LB)
  ├── Has IP ✅
  ├── IP changes dynamically ❌ not fixed
  └── Use DNS name always

NLB (Network LB)
  ├── Has IP ✅
  ├── Can have STATIC IP ✅  ← big difference!
  ├── One static IP per AZ
  └── Good when clients need fixed IP

CLB (Classic LB) — old, avoid
  ├── Has IP ✅
  ├── IP changes dynamically ❌
  └── Being phased out by AWS

This is actually a key difference between ALB and NLB:

ALB                          NLB
────                         ───
Dynamic IPs ❌               Static IPs ✅
Cannot whitelist by IP       Can whitelist by IP
Use DNS name                 Can use IP directly
Layer 7 (HTTP)               Layer 4 (TCP)

Bottom line:

ALB → has IP but it CHANGES → always use DNS name
NLB → has IP and it is STATIC → can use IP or DNS name
All ELBs → have IPs → but only NLB gives you static ones

